author: @christsciple
text: Hey great to hear Alex! I'm sure you have solid plans ahead for teaching. My advice is to replicate actual projects and products you were involved with in your daily (now previous) job. There are hundreds if not thousands of content creators that cover the basics of Python, SQL, PBI, etc. I think what's really lacking is not teaching the fundamentals, but showing how that ties into real-world projects and applications. I've been a data analyst/systems analyst/RPA guy/data engineer/software engineer/architect/developer for 20 years and the overwhelming majority of courses I see are foo-bar (basics of programming).  Why not cover a more complex scenario with actual real-world ties? Something like "hey I have all these different files; CSV's, txt/flat files, COSMOS/Mongo/NoSQL, JSON, and SQL data - with seemingly no commonality between them all, how do I tie these together into a dashboard to give me daily/weekly/monthly/yearly sales numbers broken down by sales person/region?" This could be broken up into a series where you show how you problem solve and adapt to unexpected outcomes or problems that arise along the way. Add features and functionality as well. You could include SQL, VBA, PowerShell/Bash, Python, a whole host of languages and approaches. It's complex and fairly time-consuming but it's also the differentiator between what your channel could be and what all others are.   For a lot of analysts the data is not straightforward nor is it in an easily consumable format. There's a lot of messy joins, conditions, parsing of various files, modelling, integration, and orchestration.  Just as a thought, you could use existing datasets like the NorthWinds db, or Kaggle, or build a scraper to obtain the data.  If I had more free time available I would create content like that myself but alas I can only offer up my ideas to others like you for the time being.  Whatever you choose, good luck to you!
